It's certainly not an exciting starter card, but I think it does a fine job introducing muddle, and it pairs well with tail whip. It certainly encourages picking up additional high cost cards early in the run so that you are more likely to get an energy discount, since muddling a 1 cost strike/defend at random is pretty sad. I think the upgrade is pretty important (though tail whips is even more critical to guarantee at least some vuln/weak), as it gives you a better shot at muddling your expensive cards, and works well with things that specifically care about muddling like mud shield. The damage is admittedly very low, probably because 1/3rd of the time it makes something else cost 0, but I think it could use a buff to at least 8 (10) damage, since the discount is so unreliable. 

There are a large number of much better muddle cards available for snecko later in the run, many of them muddling your entire hand or being very cheap, which tends to make snek bite feel much worse as the run goes on. As a starter card, it does just fine in act 1, but it doesn't really shine unless you get several expensive cards, and it only does ok into all 3 elites. I don't really understand some of the hate this specific card is getting here, starter cards don't necesarily have to be exciting or flashy, their main job is introducing the mechanics of the character and helping them out in act 1, which snek bite does just fine. I do agree in general that the random elements of snecko can feel very unfun, and make attempting to strategize and plan out a run very difficult. I would say that the unidentified cards and random range cards (tail whip, dice block) are some of sneckos biggest issues.
